WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:06.720
Good afternoon. Welcome to Level Up! Empowering industry R users with different levels of

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:14.560
experience. I'm Seth Kopelniks, a data scientist at Picnic Health, and I work on a team of seven

00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:18.480
wonderful data scientists and analysts, and we all come from different backgrounds.

00:00:19.120 --> 00:00:26.320
We have different backgrounds in education. My manager is a PhD linguist, and I also work with

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:34.720
PhDs in neuroscience and biostatistics, MPH in epidemiology, and we have different work histories.

00:00:36.639 --> 00:00:43.520
My co-worker Chris came from the operations side of our company as a data analyst. We have people

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:51.439
who came from educational, non-profit policy advocacy, and we have people who came from

00:00:51.439 --> 00:00:58.400
clinical research. We also have different backgrounds in our programming. A few of us

00:00:58.959 --> 00:01:06.000
are R experts from the start, or started with R and grew into experts. Others of us

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:12.720
have more knowledge in SAS before coming to Picnic Health, and a few of us had bits and

00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:19.919
pieces from various programming languages or SQL that we now bring to the team. So how do we all

00:01:19.919 --> 00:01:26.879
work together? This talk is like a mullet. A mullet is a hairstyle with business in the front and a

00:01:26.879 --> 00:01:34.879
party in the back, so this talk is going to have technology in the front as solutions for leveling

00:01:34.879 --> 00:01:41.360
up our team, and then we're going to move on to cultural solutions. So the technological solutions

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:47.279
might sound familiar to many of you, but the cultural ones, although they do come up, I feel

00:01:47.279 --> 00:01:51.360
like we discuss less in our community, so I'm excited to talk about those with you today.

00:01:53.599 --> 00:01:59.599
So first, technology. The first tool that I'm going to share with you out of two is building

00:01:59.599 --> 00:02:06.080
your own internal R packages. We speak a lot about building R packages for a wider community,

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:11.839
sharing them as open source software, which is great, but we can't always do that, and if we're

00:02:11.839 --> 00:02:18.240
working on proprietary projects, we still will want to be able to take advantage of the features

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:25.039
of R packages. So why would we want to do that? We don't want to reinvent the wheel when we're

00:02:25.039 --> 00:02:31.839
reusing code, and we'd like to reduce boilerplate. So when we're working on the clinical data that

00:02:31.839 --> 00:02:36.479
Picnic Health produces, it might come up that we want to calculate the age of our patients on a

00:02:36.479 --> 00:02:41.199
certain date, and to do that, we'll need the birth date and, if relevant, the death date.

00:02:41.199 --> 00:02:45.839
The calculation is fairly straightforward, but we'd rather make sure that we're doing it correctly

00:02:45.839 --> 00:02:50.800
once, and then using that correct solution throughout our code, instead of copying and

00:02:50.800 --> 00:02:56.880
pasting, possibly with errors, throughout many scripts. It's also nice that updating the package

00:02:56.880 --> 00:03:03.839
updates your code. So if in our internal data source, our birth date column changes name to

00:03:03.839 --> 00:03:09.839
date of birth, we can update in our package what column we're referring to, and then our code

00:03:09.839 --> 00:03:15.600
doesn't need to think about that further. And finally, it's always nice when team members are

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:20.399
using the same functionality, even when they're working on different projects, because it increases

00:03:20.399 --> 00:03:26.960
interoperability, so when I'm handing off work to a teammate, they can pick up running, and when I'm

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:32.240
reading code in a code review, or I'm trying to figure out what a co-worker did who's no longer

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:40.479
at the company, I have more familiarity with what they were doing. One sign that you might need an

00:03:40.479 --> 00:03:46.320
R package is if your scripts all begin with a laundry list of functions that you wrote elsewhere.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:52.639
So in this example, you're actually already 80% of the way to your package, because all of your

00:03:52.639 --> 00:04:00.559
content is already there. When you're building your internal R package, I encourage you to start small

00:04:00.559 --> 00:04:06.720
with a list of a handful of functions that you've already written. This way, you're focusing on the

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:10.880
process of building the package and not getting bogged down in the content, which you can always

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:18.880
expand later. So start small and iterate. Get your package to build without errors so that it works,

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:26.399
and use your package yourself. Then you can share it with others. Beyond that, there are all sorts

00:04:26.399 --> 00:04:32.160
of fancy things you can do, like building a package gem website or writing tests, but before you can

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:40.079
run, you can walk. So begin small. It's good enough if you have tons of warnings and notes

00:04:40.079 --> 00:04:47.519
when you run devtools check, which tells you how well your package is building, as long as we have

00:04:47.519 --> 00:04:54.959
zero errors for now. For further reading, the standard text by Hadley Wickham and Jenny Bryan

00:04:54.959 --> 00:05:01.119
is called R packages, and it's available for free online. There is a package called devtools,

00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:07.359
which you use, and this is all the same literature, whether you're writing an open source package or an

00:05:07.359 --> 00:05:12.559
internal package. There was a talk at this conference last year about writing your first R

00:05:12.559 --> 00:05:20.959
package, and for a slightly more advanced approach, you can host your package on Posit Package Manager,

00:05:20.959 --> 00:05:26.799
which is a paid Posit product. This is what we do at Picnic Health, so once we've set up our

00:05:26.799 --> 00:05:31.600
options, we just have to write install.packages with the package name, just as we would

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:39.279
for a package from CRAN. The second technological solution I want to share with you is hosting

00:05:39.279 --> 00:05:45.600
content on Posit Connect. If you're like me, you've heard a lot about Posit Connect over the past few

00:05:45.600 --> 00:05:51.119
days, so even if you had never heard of it before, you now might consider yourself an expert.

00:05:51.119 --> 00:05:57.839
So we'll do this quickly, but what I love about Posit Connect in terms of a team is that our work

00:05:57.839 --> 00:06:04.320
is reproducible and schedulable, so if we have a report that we're running, we don't have to worry

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:10.640
about those things, and we don't have to email attachments back and forth. So once you know the

00:06:10.640 --> 00:06:16.880
URL for your resource, you can reference it. When an update is published, it will be to the same address,

00:06:16.880 --> 00:06:23.279
so you can reference it again. And as a teaching and learning tool, teammates see the complete

00:06:23.279 --> 00:06:30.320
example of a data analysis output with the code and the resulting figures and analysis

00:06:30.959 --> 00:06:38.399
explanation, which really helps link the programming and the resulting product in the mind.

00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:46.160
So Posit Connect is a little bit harder to just get started with than writing an R package, because

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:52.320
it is a paid product. I suggest that you discuss with your team if this is something that you'd

00:06:52.320 --> 00:06:58.559
like to involve, and then talk to one of the many people from Posit at this conference who would love

00:06:58.559 --> 00:07:07.119
to tell you more. All right, we've made it through the business in the front, and now we have our party.

00:07:07.359 --> 00:07:14.720
So now I'm talking about cultural solutions to upskilling our team together. And the first one

00:07:14.720 --> 00:07:21.279
is a wiki. So by a wiki, I just mean a website that is editable by its users, in this case,

00:07:21.279 --> 00:07:27.200
your teammates. Wikis are good because they are highly discoverable. So if you're not sure what

00:07:27.200 --> 00:07:32.799
you don't know, you can go to your wiki and read through it, and see what your teammates have deemed

00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:41.839
a useful and necessary knowledge for you. I also advise that when you're contributing to the wiki,

00:07:42.640 --> 00:07:47.359
advertise your contributions to your team. This will encourage them to do the same.

00:07:48.399 --> 00:07:53.200
As an example, at our company, this is what our wiki looks like. We're using a product called

00:07:53.200 --> 00:08:00.079
Gitbook to host it, which there are a lot of paid products that will do this. I don't necessarily

00:08:00.799 --> 00:08:05.519
care which one you choose, but this meets our needs. You can see we have sections about

00:08:05.519 --> 00:08:10.480
troubleshooting common errors, how to access our data, how to use our Git and GitHub setup,

00:08:11.359 --> 00:08:19.760
and much more. When you're advertising your contributions, let your teammates know what

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:25.359
you're adding, maybe give them a link to the new page, and then they can learn from what you just

00:08:25.359 --> 00:08:32.320
wrote, and they are encouraged to do the same when they edit the wiki. I also want to point out

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:38.159
that just like in our package, you might already be 80% of the way there. A Google doc can be a

00:08:38.159 --> 00:08:44.479
wiki. All we need is an editable page or website that your teammates can view, and a Google doc

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:49.520
can be that. So why not start with taking a list of bug fixes that you might have posted in Slack

00:08:49.520 --> 00:08:53.840
already and putting them in a Google doc and slapping the name of wiki on it.

00:08:56.640 --> 00:09:03.599
The next technological solution I want to share is office hours and pair programming. So by setting

00:09:03.599 --> 00:09:09.039
aside an optional meeting that we have once or twice a week with my team, and I'm coming from a

00:09:09.039 --> 00:09:17.520
team of seven, if you have a team of 50 or two, a cadence might be different, and invite folks to

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:23.840
come with their problems, their questions, maybe some work that they need a little help collaborating

00:09:23.840 --> 00:09:33.599
on, and share your knowledge with one another. For example, you might talk about resolving merge

00:09:33.599 --> 00:09:40.239
conflicts in Git, or updating a function in your package, or even set differences between vectors

00:09:40.239 --> 00:09:50.880
in R. We can also share our knowledge directly with our teammates, not waiting for a meeting.

00:09:52.239 --> 00:09:57.200
We don't want to hoard our knowledge. We want to share it. And we can use whatever format our team

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:03.440
usually uses to communicate. So if you are an in-person team and you always hang by each other's

00:10:03.440 --> 00:10:09.520
cubicles, go ahead and chat. If you are on a remote-first team like me, share in Slack or

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:17.119
Teams, whatever you use, email, the format doesn't really matter. What matters is that we're sharing

00:10:17.119 --> 00:10:23.119
our knowledge. For example, maybe you found a blog post about ordering the colors of your legend so

00:10:23.119 --> 00:10:29.119
they match the order of colors from top to bottom in your plot. Or maybe you found that two functions

00:10:29.119 --> 00:10:35.840
that you use a lot can sometimes return multiple values instead of just one. Let your teammates

00:10:35.840 --> 00:10:40.400
know the same since they're likely to be using the same functions, encountering the same issues,

00:10:40.960 --> 00:10:48.080
or wanting to pretty up their plots in the same way. The inverse of sharing a public service

00:10:48.080 --> 00:10:53.599
announcement is asking for help. If you're wondering something and you haven't found the

00:10:53.599 --> 00:10:59.119
answer yet, well, others might be monitoring the same thing. Set an example that it's okay

00:10:59.679 --> 00:11:08.960
to need help. And make yourself approachable. This goes especially for senior team members.

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:15.760
So again, on a remote team, especially a bigger remote team, it can be difficult to post in a

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:24.080
public forum or chat where everyone can see that you don't know what you're doing. And as a senior

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:29.520
team member, you can set an example, show that's okay, and become more approachable.

00:11:32.159 --> 00:11:38.159
And I want to emphasize that even if it takes 65 replies to get to the bottom of your book,

00:11:38.719 --> 00:11:44.719
you have now saved a bunch of other people 65 replies worth of work to solve your issue.

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:51.039
Another example that we can share for technological solutions

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:56.640
is demoing your work. So here my coworker Ashley is showing a dashboard that she made.

00:11:58.559 --> 00:12:04.640
And she's showing what's possible given the tools that we already have. Or new tools that she has

00:12:04.640 --> 00:12:12.400
implemented in our stack. It's also great to get feedback on your work from coworkers more senior

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:18.400
or more junior than you. And the audience here can be small. So just the people you work closest

00:12:18.400 --> 00:12:27.119
with or it could even be your entire company. So what do all of these solutions have in common?

00:12:27.119 --> 00:12:33.440
I see two things. First, you can start unilaterally. Regardless of your seniority

00:12:33.440 --> 00:12:38.159
and regardless if you control the first strings, you can build a Google Doc

00:12:38.159 --> 00:12:42.960
of your favorite bug fixes. Or you can share a blog post that you really love.

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:49.760
And secondly, you can lead by example. By doing any of these things, you are showing it's something

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:56.479
that's okay to do and you're encouraging your coworkers to do the same. As a result,

00:12:57.599 --> 00:13:05.919
your work will become faster, smarter, and more legible to your teammates. And your team will level up.

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:09.280
Thank you.

00:13:13.919 --> 00:13:20.479
Here you can see my LinkedIn, my email, and a link to the slides, as well as the QR code to the slides.

00:13:21.039 --> 00:13:24.880
And I believe we have some time for Q&A on Slido.

00:13:26.159 --> 00:13:31.919
That's correct. Thank you so much for your talk. So I have a question here. It says,

00:13:31.919 --> 00:13:37.679
the tool is amazing. I would love to use but I'm not working with U.S. data. Any scope of

00:13:37.679 --> 00:13:42.880
translating this tool to other countries? What is needed for that in terms of census data?

00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:48.239
Something tells me this is the wrong one. That might be a different talk. It does look like a

00:13:48.239 --> 00:14:00.080
different talk. I am reading directly. I'm in the right room. Okay. So can you give us an example

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:06.000
of like the first functions that you used in your package that you published internally?

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:15.039
Yes. So we have a lot of utilities for using our data that we share with our research partners.

00:14:15.039 --> 00:14:21.520
So things like accessing the patient's age or span between their first and last visit or their

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:28.479
geographic location. We also have a whole other package that we use not to manipulate our data,

00:14:28.479 --> 00:14:33.359
but just to serve as infrastructure for connecting to our databases,

00:14:33.919 --> 00:14:41.359
and authenticating with Google, authenticating with RStudio Connect. So that's like a whole

00:14:41.359 --> 00:14:46.719
other list of utilities that can come with your internal package.

00:14:47.679 --> 00:14:51.119
That's awesome. Now we have one for this actual room.

00:14:52.960 --> 00:14:56.400
It says, do you have any advice for people who are a team of one?

00:14:57.280 --> 00:15:02.640
Good question. So the intended audience of the talk was people on a team of two or more,

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:10.479
but on a team of one, although you might not get the same benefit from sharing a demo,

00:15:11.119 --> 00:15:19.119
you might still have advantages from using an R package. Like you have the same capabilities

00:15:19.840 --> 00:15:28.159
of integrating with the RStudio IDE. You can run tests and documentation. I think largely anything

00:15:28.159 --> 00:15:33.359
involving writing things down to act as an artificial memory enhancer is still going to

00:15:33.359 --> 00:15:38.080
be impactful as a team of one. Because I can't tell you the number of times I've searched my

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:43.440
problem in the Wiki or in my company Slack and found that I was the one who had the same problem

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:48.320
six months ago. So maybe the same will work as a team of one. I don't know.

00:15:49.440 --> 00:15:56.000
I'm very familiar to having the same problem six months ago. All right. So I like this one

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:00.799
a lot. It says, how do you motivate colleagues to get on board with new cultural practices?

00:16:01.679 --> 00:16:08.080
It's a good question. I am lucky to have a team that is very on board with positive cultural

00:16:08.719 --> 00:16:16.880
practices. So I can't really speak to the other side from experience, but from what I can tell you

00:16:16.880 --> 00:16:24.000
is that if people are seeing how it directly benefits them, they're more likely to buy in.

00:16:24.559 --> 00:16:30.320
So if someone has a question and you know the answer because it's already on the Wiki,

00:16:30.960 --> 00:16:35.599
you can share a link to the Wiki. Or conversely, if someone solved a question,

00:16:37.119 --> 00:16:40.880
answered a question that you had, maybe you can add that to the Wiki for them

00:16:40.880 --> 00:16:48.640
and let them know and that can show the benefits. That's great. I think we have time for one last

00:16:48.640 --> 00:16:54.400
question. It says, where do you store your internal packages and how do you get them

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:59.760
on Connect? Is it Package Manager or something else? Yes, we do use Posit Package Manager

00:17:00.559 --> 00:17:07.119
and we have it set up so that it reads directly from our GitHub, which is private as we are a

00:17:07.119 --> 00:17:13.119
private company. So we have a few packages that go to Posit Package Manager. They are rebuilt

00:17:13.119 --> 00:17:19.680
whenever a commit is made in the relevant package and we can see them once we have our

00:17:20.319 --> 00:17:30.959
options in R configured appropriately. Well, thank you again. I appreciate it. Thank you.

00:17:37.119 --> 00:17:37.619
Thank you.

